# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: discrete-geometry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] Discrete geometry has a large overlap with convex geometry and computational geometry, and is closely related to subjects such as finite geometry, combinatorial optimization, digital geometry, discrete differential geometry, geometric graph theory, toric geometry, and combinatorial topology.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] Polyhedra and tessellations had been studied for many years by people such as Kepler and Cauchy, modern discrete geometry has its origins in the late 19th century.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] Early topics studied were: the density of circle packings by Thue, projective configurations by Reye and Steinitz, the geometry of numbers by Minkowski, and map colourings by Tait, Heawood, and Hadwiger.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] Coxeter, and Paul Erdős laid the foundations of *discrete geometry*.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] A **polytope** is a geometric object with flat sides, which exists in any general number of dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] A polygon is a polytope in two dimensions, a polyhedron in three dimensions, and so on in higher dimensions (such as a 4-polytope in four dimensions).
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] Some theories further generalize the idea to include such objects as unbounded polytopes (apeirotopes and tessellations), and abstract polytopes.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] Packings, coverings, and tilings are all ways of arranging uniform objects (typically circles, spheres, or tiles) in a regular way on a surface or manifold.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] A **sphere packing** is an arrangement of non-overlapping spheres within a containing space.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] The spheres considered are usually all of identical size, and the space is usually three-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] However, sphere packing problems can be generalised to consider unequal spheres, *n*-dimensional Euclidean space (where the problem becomes circle packing in two dimensions, or hypersphere packing in higher dimensions) or to non-Euclidean spaces such as hyperbolic space.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] A **tessellation** of a flat surface is the tiling of a plane using one or more geometric shapes, called tiles, with no overlaps and no gaps.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] In mathematics, tessellations can be generalized to higher dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] Incidence structures generalize planes (such as affine, projective, and Möbius planes) as can be seen from their axiomatic definitions.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] Incidence structures also generalize the higher-dimensional analogs and the finite structures are sometimes called finite geometries.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] where *P* is a set of "points", *L* is a set of "lines" and $I\subseteq P\times L$ is the incidence relation.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] we say that point *p* "lies on" line l .
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] An **oriented matroid** is a mathematical structure that abstracts the properties of directed graphs and of arrangements of vectors in a vector space over an ordered field (particularly for partially ordered vector spaces).
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] In comparison, an ordinary (i.e., non-oriented) matroid abstracts the dependence properties that are common both to graphs, which are not necessarily *directed*, and to arrangements of vectors over fields, which are not necessarily *ordered*.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] A **geometric graph** is a graph in which the vertices or edges are associated with geometric objects.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] Examples include Euclidean graphs, the 1-skeleton of a polyhedron or polytope, unit disk graphs, and visibility graphs.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] A **simplicial complex** is a topological space of a certain kind, constructed by "gluing together" points, line segments, triangles, and their *n*-dimensional counterparts (see illustration).
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] Simplicial complexes should not be confused with the more abstract notion of a simplicial set appearing in modern simplicial homotopy theory.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] The purely combinatorial counterpart to a simplicial complex is an abstract simplicial complex.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] The discipline of combinatorial topology used combinatorial concepts in topology and in the early 20th century this turned into the field of algebraic topology.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] In 1978, the situation was reversed – methods from algebraic topology were used to solve a problem in combinatorics – when László Lovász proved the Kneser conjecture, thus beginning the new study of **topological combinatorics**.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] Lovász's proof used the Borsuk-Ulam theorem and this theorem retains a prominent role in this new field.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] This theorem has many equivalent versions and analogs and has been used in the study of fair division problems.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] A **discrete group** is a group *G* equipped with the discrete topology.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] With this topology, *G* becomes a topological group.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] A **discrete subgroup** of a topological group *G* is a subgroup *H* whose relative topology is the discrete one.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] For example, the integers, **Z**, form a discrete subgroup of the reals, **R** (with the standard metric topology), but the rational numbers, **Q**, do not.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] A **lattice** in a locally compact topological group is a discrete subgroup with the property that the quotient space has finite invariant measure.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] In the special case of subgroups of **R***n*, this amounts to the usual geometric notion of a lattice, and both the algebraic structure of lattices and the geometry of the totality of all lattices are relatively well understood.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] Deep results of Borel, Harish-Chandra, Mostow, Tamagawa, M.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] Raghunathan, Margulis, Zimmer obtained from the 1950s through the 1970s provided examples and generalized much of the theory to the setting of nilpotent Lie groups and semisimple algebraic groups over a local field.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] In the 1990s, Bass and Lubotzky initiated the study of *tree lattices*, which remains an active research area.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] Simply put, **digitizing** is replacing an object by a discrete set of its points.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] The images we see on the TV screen, the raster display of a computer, or in newspapers are in fact digital images.
[src:discrete-geometry/discrete-geometry] Its main application areas are computer graphics and image analysis.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] In geometry, an **incidence** relation is a heterogeneous relation that captures the idea being expressed when phrases such as "a point *lies on* a line" or "a line is *contained in* a plane" are used.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] The most basic incidence relation is that between a point, *P*, and a line, *l*, sometimes denoted *P* I *l*.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] If *P* and *l* are incident, *P* I *l*, the pair (*P*, *l*) is called a *flag*.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] Statements such as "line *l*1 intersects line *l*2" are also statements about incidence relations, but in this case, it is because this is a shorthand way of saying that "there exists a point *P* that is incident with both line *l*1 and line *l*2".
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] When one type of object can be thought of as a set of the other type of object (*viz*., a plane is a set of points) then an incidence relation may be viewed as containment.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] Statements such as "any two lines in a plane meet" are called *incidence propositions*.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] This particular statement is true in a projective plane, though not true in the Euclidean plane where lines may be parallel.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] Historically, projective geometry was developed in order to make the propositions of incidence true without exceptions, such as those caused by the existence of parallels.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] From the point of view of synthetic geometry, projective geometry *should be* developed using such propositions as axioms.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] This is most significant for projective planes due to the universal validity of Desargues' theorem in higher dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] In contrast, the analytic approach is to define projective space based on linear algebra and utilizing homogeneous co-ordinates.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] The propositions of incidence are derived from the following basic result on vector spaces: given subspaces *U* and *W* of a (finite-dimensional) vector space *V*, the dimension of their intersection is dim *U* + dim *W* − dim (*U* + *W*).
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] The following sections are limited to projective planes defined over fields, often denoted by PG(2, *F*), where *F* is a field, or **P**2*F*.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] However these computations can be naturally extended to higher-dimensional projective spaces, and the field may be replaced by a division ring (or skewfield) provided that one pays attention to the fact that multiplication is not commutative in that case.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] Let *V* be the three-dimensional vector space defined over the field *F*.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] The projective plane **P**(*V*) = PG(2, *F*) consists of the one-dimensional vector subspaces of *V*, called *points*, and the two-dimensional vector subspaces of *V*, called *lines*.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] Incidence of a point and a line is given by containment of the one-dimensional subspace in the two-dimensional subspace.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] Fix a basis for *V* so that we may describe its vectors as coordinate triples (with respect to that basis).
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] A one-dimensional vector subspace consists of a non-zero vector and all of its scalar multiples.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] The non-zero scalar multiples, written as coordinate triples, are the homogeneous coordinates of the given point, called *point coordinates*.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] With respect to this basis, the solution space of a single linear equation {(*x*, *y*, *z*) | *ax* + *by* + *cz* = 0} is a two-dimensional subspace of *V*, and hence a line of **P**(*V*).
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] This line may be denoted by *line coordinates* [*a*, *b*, *c*], which are also homogeneous coordinates since non-zero scalar multiples would give the same line.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] Point coordinates may be written as column vectors, (*x*, *y*, *z*)T, with colons, (*x* : *y* : *z*), or with a subscript, (*x*, *y*, *z*)P.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] Correspondingly, line coordinates may be written as row vectors, (*a*, *b*, *c*), with colons, [*a* : *b* : *c*] or with a subscript, (*a*, *b*, *c*)L.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] No matter what notation is employed, when the homogeneous coordinates of the point and line are just considered as ordered triples, their incidence is expressed as having their dot product equal 0.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] Let *P*1 and *P*2 be a pair of distinct points with homogeneous coordinates (*x*1, *y*1, *z*1) and (*x*2, *y*2, *z*2) respectively.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] Expansion of this determinantal equation produces a homogeneous linear equation, which must be the equation of line *l*.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] Points that are incident with the same line are said to be *collinear*.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] The set of all points incident with the same line is called a range.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] i.e., if and only if the determinant of the homogeneous coordinates of the points is equal to zero.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] According to the Gram determinant test, whether the matrix P above has less than full rank is equivalent to $\det(P^{\mathsf {T}}P)=0$ .
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] The coefficients of *a*, *b* and *c* in this equation give the homogeneous coordinates of *P*.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] Lines that meet at the same point are said to be *concurrent*.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] The set of all lines in a plane incident with the same point is called a *pencil of lines* centered at that point.
[src:discrete-geometry/incidence-geometry] The computation of the intersection of two lines shows that the entire pencil of lines centered at a point is determined by any two of the lines that intersect at that point.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] In geometry, the **kissing number** of a mathematical space is defined as the greatest number of non-overlapping unit spheres (i.e., of radius 1) that can be arranged in that space such that they each touch a common unit sphere.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] For a given sphere packing (arrangement of spheres) in a given space, a kissing number can also be defined for each individual sphere as the number of spheres it touches.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] For a lattice packing, the kissing number is the same for every sphere; but for an arbitrary sphere packing, the kissing number may vary from one sphere to another.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] Other names for kissing number that have been used are **Newton number** (after the originator of the problem), and **contact number**.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] In general, the **kissing number problem** seeks the maximum possible kissing number for n-dimensional spheres in (*n* + 1)-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] Ordinary spheres correspond to two-dimensional closed surfaces in three-dimensional space.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] Finding the kissing number when centers of spheres are confined to a line (the one-dimensional case) or a plane (two-dimensional case) is trivial.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] Proving a solution to the three-dimensional case, despite being easy to conceptualise and model in the physical world, eluded mathematicians until the mid-20th century.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] Solutions in higher dimensions are considerably more challenging, and only a handful of cases have been solved exactly.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] For others, investigations have determined upper and lower bounds based on the sum of squares hierarchy of semidefinite programs, but not exact solutions.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] Assume by contradiction that there are more than six touching circles.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] Then at least two adjacent rays, say *CC*1 and *CC*2, are separated by an angle of less than 60°.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] The segments CCi have the same length – 2*r* – for all i.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] Therefore, the triangle △*CC*1*C*2 is isosceles, and its third side – *C*1*C*2 – has a side length of less than 2*r*.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] Therefore, the circles 1 and 2 intersect – a contradiction.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] In three dimensions, the kissing number is 12, but the correct value was much more difficult to establish than in dimensions one and two.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] It is easy to arrange 12 spheres so that each touches a central sphere, with a lot of space left over, and it is not obvious that there is no way to pack in a 13th sphere.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] (In fact, there is so much extra space that any two of the 12 outer spheres can exchange places through a continuous movement without any of the outer spheres losing contact with the center one.) This was the subject of a famous disagreement between mathematicians Isaac Newton and David Gregory.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] Newton correctly thought that the limit was 12; Gregory thought that a 13th could fit.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] Some incomplete proofs that Newton was correct were offered in the 19th century, most notably one by Reinhold Hoppe, but the first correct proof (according to Brass, Moser, and Pach) did not appear until 1953 by Schütte and van der Waerden.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] The twelve neighbors of the central sphere correspond to the maximum bulk coordination number of an atom in a crystal lattice in which all atoms have the same size (as in a chemical element).
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] A coordination number of 12 is found in a cubic close-packed or a hexagonal close-packed structure.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] In four dimensions, the kissing number is 24.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] The existence of the highly symmetrical E8 lattice and Leech lattice has allowed to determine the kissing number for *n* = 8 (namely, 240) and for *n* = 24 (namely, 196,560).
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] The kissing number in n dimensions is unknown for other values of n.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] If arrangements are restricted to *lattice* arrangements, in which the centres of the spheres all lie on points in a lattice, then this restricted kissing number is known for *n* = 1 to 9 and *n* = 24 dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] For 5, 6, and 7 dimensions, the arrangement with the highest known kissing number found so far is the optimal lattice arrangement, but the existence of a non-lattice arrangement with a higher kissing number has not been excluded.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] The following table lists some known bounds on the kissing number in various dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] The dimensions in which the kissing number is known are listed in boldface.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] The kissing number problem can be generalized to the problem of finding the maximum number of non-overlapping congruent copies of any convex body that touch a given copy of the body.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] There are different versions of the problem, depending on whether the copies are only required to be congruent to the original body, translates of the original body, or translated by a lattice.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] For example, for the regular tetrahedron, it is known that both the lattice kissing number and the translative kissing number are equal to 18, whereas the congruent kissing number is at least 56.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] There are several approximation algorithms on intersection graphs where the approximation ratio depends on the kissing number.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] For example, there is a polynomial-time 10-approximation algorithm to find a maximum non-intersecting subset of a set of rotated unit squares.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] The kissing number problem can be stated as the existence of a solution to a set of inequalities.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] Let xn be a set of N D-dimensional position vectors of sphere centres.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] Thus the problem for each dimension can be expressed in the existential theory of the reals.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] However, general methods of solving problems in this form take at least exponential time; that is why this problem has only been solved up to four dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] Therefore, to solve the case in *D* = 5 dimensions and *N* = 40 + 1 vectors would be equivalent to determining the existence of real solutions to a quartic polynomial in 1025 variables.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] This must be supplemented with the condition that the Cayley–Menger determinant is zero for any set of points which forms a (*D* + 1)-simplex in D dimensions, since that volume must be zero.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] Setting $R_{mn}=1+y_{mn}^{2}$ gives a set of simultaneous polynomial equations in just y which must be solved for real values only.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] The two methods, being entirely equivalent, have various different uses.
[src:discrete-geometry/kissing-number] For example, in the second case, one can randomly alter the values of the y by small amounts to try to minimise the polynomial in terms of the y.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] One of the simplest examples of a lattice is the square lattice, which consists of all points $(a,b)$ in the plane whose coordinates are both integers, and its higher-dimensional analogues the integer lattices $\mathbb {Z} ^{n}$ .
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Closure under addition and subtraction means that a lattice must be a subgroup of the additive group of the points in the space.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] The requirements of minimum and maximum distance can be summarized by saying that a lattice is a Delone set.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] More abstractly, a lattice can be described as a free abelian group of dimension n which spans the vector space ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ⁠.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] For any basis of ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ⁠, the subgroup of all linear combinations with integer coefficients of the basis vectors forms a lattice, and every lattice can be formed from a basis in this way.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] A lattice may be viewed as a regular tiling of a space by a primitive cell.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Lattices have many significant applications in pure mathematics, particularly in connection to Lie algebras, number theory and group theory.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] They also arise in applied mathematics in connection with coding theory, in percolation theory to study connectivity arising from small-scale interactions, cryptography because of conjectured computational hardness of several lattice problems, and occur frequently in the physical sciences.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] For instance, in materials science and solid-state physics, a lattice is a synonym for a crystalline structure, a 3-dimensional array of regularly spaced points coinciding in special cases with the atom or molecule positions in a crystal.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] More generally, lattice models are studied in physics, often by the techniques of computational physics.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] A lattice is the symmetry group of discrete translational symmetry in *n* directions.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] A pattern with this lattice of translational symmetry cannot have more, but may have less symmetry than the lattice itself.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] As a group (dropping its geometric structure) a lattice is a finitely generated free abelian group, and thus isomorphic to ⁠ $\mathbb {Z} ^{n}$ ⁠.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] A simple example of a lattice in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is the subgroup ⁠ $\mathbb {Z} ^{n}$ ⁠.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] More complicated examples include the E8 lattice, which is a lattice in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{8}$ ⁠, and the Leech lattice in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{24}$ ⁠.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] The period lattice in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ is central to the study of elliptic functions, developed in nineteenth century mathematics; it generalizes to higher dimensions in the theory of abelian functions.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Lattices called root lattices are important in the theory of simple Lie algebras; for example, the E8 lattice is related to a Lie algebra that goes by the same name.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Any other basis ${\textstyle \{v_{1}',v_{2}',\ldots ,v_{n}'\}}$ with matrix *M'* is related by an automorphism of the group $\Lambda \cong \mathbb {Z} ^{n}$ , meaning $M'=AM$ for an integer transition matrix $A\in \mathrm {GL} _{n}(\mathbb {Z} )$ having $\det(A)=\pm 1$ .
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] A lattice fills the whole of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ with equal tiles, copies of the *n*-dimensional parallelepiped spanned by the basis vectors, known as the *fundamental domain* or *primitive cell* of the lattice.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] The *n*-dimensional volume of this fundamental domain is sometimes called the **covolume** of the lattice: it is invariant for any basis, and may be computed as $d(\Lambda )=|\det(M)|$ .
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] (If the *n*-dimensional lattice *$\Lambda$* lies in a higher-dimensional space $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ , its basis forms an *m* x *n* matrix whose volume can be computed using the Gram matrix: $d(\Lambda )={\sqrt {\det M^{t}M}}$ .) A lattice with $d(\Lambda )=1$ is called unimodular.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Minkowski's theorem relates the number ⁠ $\mathrm {d} (\Lambda )$ ⁠, or more generally the volume of a symmetric convex set S , to the number of lattice points contained in ⁠ S ⁠.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] For a polytope whose vertices are elements of the lattice, the number of lattice points it contains is described by the polytope's Ehrhart polynomial.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Formulas for some of the coefficients of this polynomial involve ⁠ $\mathrm {d} (\Lambda )$ ⁠ as well.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Computational lattice problems have many applications in computer science.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] There are five 2D lattice types as given by the crystallographic restriction theorem.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Below, the wallpaper group of the lattice $\Lambda$ is given in IUCr notation, Orbifold notation, and Coxeter notation, along with a wallpaper diagram showing the symmetry domains.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Note that a pattern with this lattice of translational symmetry cannot have more, but may have less symmetry than the lattice itself.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] For example, below the hexagonal/triangular lattice is given twice, with full 6-fold and a half 3-fold reflectional symmetry.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] If the symmetry group of a pattern contains an *n*-fold rotation then the lattice has *n*-fold symmetry for even *n* and 2*n*-fold for odd *n*.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] For the classification of a given lattice, start with one point and take a nearest second point.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] For the third point, not on the same line, consider its distances to both points.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Among the points for which the smaller of these two distances is least, choose a point for which the larger of the two is least.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] The five cases correspond to the triangle being equilateral, right isosceles, right, isosceles, and scalene.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] In a rhombic lattice, the shortest distance may either be a diagonal or a side of the rhombus, i.e., the line segment connecting the first two points may or may not be one of the equal sides of the isosceles triangle.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] This depends on the smaller angle of the rhombus being less than 60° or between 60° and 90°.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] The general case is known as a period lattice.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] The vectors {**p**,**q**} are a generator pair or a basis of the lattice $\Lambda$ .
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] This ensures that **p** and **q** themselves are integer linear combinations of the other two vectors.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Each basis pair {**p**, **q**} defines a parallelogram, all with the same area given by the magnitude of the cross product **p** x **q**.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] This parallelogram is a fundamental parallelogram of the translation symmetries, i.e. a fundamental domain or primitive cell.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] The basis vectors {**p,q**} can be represented by complex numbers.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Up to changing the scaling of the lattice and rotating it, the pair {**p,q**} can be represented by their complex number quotient: if we fix two standard lattice points 0 and 1 in the complex plane, the lattice shape is determined by the third lattice point *z = p*/*q*.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] The figure shows the action of the modular group acting on the complex plane $\mathbb {C}$ (not to be confused with the lattice translating the real plane $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ ).
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Each "curved triangle" in the image is a fundamental domain of the modular group, contain one complex number for each 2D lattice $\Lambda$ up to scaling and rotation.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] The grey area is a standard fundamental domain, corresponding to the canonical representation of $\Lambda$ with 0 and 1 being two lattice points that are closest to each other; duplication is avoided by including only half of the boundary.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] The rhombic lattices are represented by the points on the boundary, with the hexagonal lattice as vertex, and *i* for the square lattice.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] The rectangular lattices are at the imaginary axis, and the remaining area represents the parallelogram lattices, with the mirror image of a parallelogram represented by the mirror image in the imaginary axis.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] The 14 lattice types in 3D are called **Bravais lattices**.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] They are characterized by their space group.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] 3D patterns with translational symmetry of a particular type cannot have more, but may have less, symmetry than the lattice itself.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] A lattice in $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ is a discrete subgroup of $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ which spans $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ as a real vector space.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] As the dimension of $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ as a real vector space is equal to ⁠ $2n$ ⁠, a lattice in $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ will be a free abelian group of rank ⁠ $2n$ ⁠.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] For example, the Gaussian integers $\mathbb {Z} [i]=\mathbb {Z} +i\mathbb {Z}$ form a lattice in ⁠ $\mathbb {C} =\mathbb {C} ^{1}$ ⁠, as $(1,i)$ is a basis of $\mathbb {C}$ over ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] More generally, a **lattice** Γ in a Lie group *G* is a discrete subgroup, such that the quotient *G*/Γ is of finite measure, for the measure on it inherited from Haar measure on *G* (left-invariant, or right-invariant—the definition is independent of that choice).
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] That will certainly be the case when *G*/Γ is compact, but that sufficient condition is not necessary, as is shown by the case of the modular group in SL2(**R**), which is a lattice but where the quotient isn't compact (it has *cusps*).
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] There are general results stating the existence of lattices in Lie groups.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] A lattice is said to be **uniform** or **cocompact** if *G*/Γ is compact; otherwise the lattice is called **non-uniform**.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] While we normally consider $\mathbb {Z}$ lattices in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ this concept can be generalized to any finite-dimensional vector space over any field.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Let *K* be a field, let *V* be an *n*-dimensional *K*-vector space, let $B=\{\mathbf {v} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {v} _{n}\}$ be a *K*-basis for *V* and let *R* be a ring contained within *K*.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] In general, different bases *B* will generate different lattices.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Important cases of such lattices occur in number theory with *K* a *p*-adic field and T the *p*-adic integers.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] A **primitive element** of a lattice is an element $v\in \Lambda$ that is not a positive integer multiple of another element in the lattice.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] Every one-dimensional sublattice $\Gamma \subset \Lambda$ has a primitive generator which is unique up to sign.
[src:discrete-geometry/lattice-group] More generally, consider an $\ell$ -dimensional sublattice $\Gamma \subset \mathbb {Z} ^{n}$ with a basis $\{v_{1},\ldots ,v_{\ell }\}$ whose column vectors form a matrix $M\in \mathrm {M} _{n\times \ell }(\mathbb {Z} )$ .
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In elementary geometry, a **polytope** is a geometric object with flat sides (*faces*).
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Polytopes are the generalization of three-dimensional polyhedra to any number of dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Polytopes may exist in any general number of dimensions n as an n-dimensional polytope or **n-polytope**.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] For example, a two-dimensional polygon is a 2-polytope and a three-dimensional polyhedron is a 3-polytope.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In this context, "flat sides" means that the sides of a (*k* + 1)-polytope consist of k-polytopes that may have (*k* − 1)-polytopes in common.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Some theories further generalize the idea to include such objects as unbounded apeirotopes and tessellations, decompositions or tilings of curved manifolds including spherical polyhedra, and set-theoretic abstract polytopes.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Polytopes of more than three dimensions were first discovered by Ludwig Schläfli before 1853, who called such a figure a **polyschem**.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] The German term *Polytop* was coined by the mathematician Reinhold Hoppe, and was introduced to English mathematicians as *polytope* by Alicia Boole Stott.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Nowadays, the term *polytope* is a broad term that covers a wide class of objects, and various definitions appear in the mathematical literature.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Many of these definitions are not equivalent to each other, resulting in different overlapping sets of objects being called *polytopes*.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] They represent different approaches to generalizing the convex polytopes to include other objects with similar properties.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] The original approach broadly followed by Ludwig Schläfli, Thorold Gosset and others begins with the extension by analogy into four or more dimensions, of the idea of a polygon and polyhedron respectively in two and three dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Attempts to generalise the Euler characteristic of polyhedra to higher-dimensional polytopes led to the development of topology and the treatment of a decomposition or CW-complex as analogous to a polytope.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In this approach, a polytope may be regarded as a tessellation or decomposition of some given manifold.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] An example of this approach defines a polytope as a set of points that admits a simplicial decomposition.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In this definition, a polytope is the union of finitely many simplices, with the additional property that, for any two simplices that have a nonempty intersection, their intersection is a vertex, edge, or higher dimensional face of the two.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] However this definition does not allow star polytopes with interior structures, and so is restricted to certain areas of mathematics.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] The discovery of star polyhedra and other unusual constructions led to the idea of a polyhedron as a bounding surface, ignoring its interior.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In this light convex polytopes in *p*-space are equivalent to tilings of the (*p*−1)-sphere, while others may be tilings of other elliptic, flat or toroidal (*p*−1)-surfaces – see elliptic tiling and toroidal polyhedron.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] A polyhedron is understood as a surface whose faces are polygons, a 4-polytope as a hypersurface whose facets (cells) are polyhedra, and so forth.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] The idea of constructing a higher polytope from those of lower dimension is also sometimes extended downwards in dimension, with an (edge) seen as a 1-polytope bounded by a point pair, and a point or vertex as a 0-polytope.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] This approach is used for example in the theory of abstract polytopes.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In certain fields of mathematics, the terms "polytope" and "polyhedron" are used in a different sense: a *polyhedron* (or *n*-dimensional polyhedron) is the generic (bounded or unbounded) object in any dimension (referred to as *polytope* in this article) and *polytope* means a bounded polyhedron.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] This terminology is typically confined to polytopes and polyhedra that are convex.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] With this terminology, a convex polyhedron is the intersection of a finite number of halfspaces and is defined by its sides while a convex polytope is the convex hull of a finite number of points and is defined by its vertices.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] A polytope comprises elements of different dimensionality such as vertices, edges, faces, cells and so on.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Terminology for these is not fully consistent across different authors.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] For example, some authors use *face* to refer to an (*n* − 1)-dimensional element while others use *face* to denote a 2-face specifically.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Authors may use *j*-face or *j*-facet to indicate an element of *j* dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Some use *edge* to refer to a ridge, while H.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Coxeter uses *cell* to denote an (*n* − 1)-dimensional element.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] An *n*-dimensional polytope is bounded by a number of (*n* − 1)-dimensional *facets*.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] These facets are themselves polytopes, whose facets are (*n* − 2)-dimensional *ridges* of the original polytope.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Every ridge arises as the intersection of two facets (but the intersection of two facets need not be a ridge).
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Ridges are once again polytopes whose facets give rise to (*n* − 3)-dimensional boundaries of the original polytope, and so on.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] These bounding sub-polytopes may be referred to as faces, or specifically *j*-dimensional faces or *j*-faces.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] A 0-dimensional face is called a *vertex*, and consists of a single point.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] A 1-dimensional face is called an *edge*, and consists of a line segment.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] A 2-dimensional face consists of a polygon, and a 3-dimensional face, sometimes called a *cell*, consists of a polyhedron.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] The convex polytopes are the simplest kind of polytopes, and form the basis for several different generalizations of the concept of polytopes.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] A convex polytope is sometimes defined as the intersection of a set of half-spaces.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] This definition allows a polytope to be neither bounded nor finite.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Polytopes are defined in this way, e.g., in linear programming.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] A polytope is *bounded* if there is a ball of finite radius that contains it.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] A polytope is said to be *pointed* if it contains at least one vertex.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Every bounded nonempty polytope is pointed.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] An example of a non-pointed polytope is the set $\{(x,y)\in \mathbb {R} ^{2}\mid x\geq 0\}$ .
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] A polytope is *finite* if it is defined in terms of a finite number of objects, e.g., as an intersection of a finite number of half-planes.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] It is an integral polytope if all of its vertices have integer coordinates.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] A certain class of convex polytopes are *reflexive* polytopes.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] An integral d -polytope ${\mathcal {P}}$ is reflexive if for some integral matrix $\mathbf {A}$ , ${\mathcal {P}}=\{\mathbf {x} \in \mathbb {R} ^{d}:\mathbf {Ax} \leq \mathbf {1} \}$ , where $\mathbf {1}$ denotes a vector of all ones, and the inequality is component-wise.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] It follows from this definition that ${\mathcal {P}}$ is reflexive if and only if $(t+1){\mathcal {P}}^{\circ }\cap \mathbb {Z} ^{d}=t{\mathcal {P}}\cap \mathbb {Z} ^{d}$ for all $t\in \mathbb {Z} _{\geq 0}$ .
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In other words, a $(t+1)$ -dilate of ${\mathcal {P}}$ differs, in terms of integer lattice points, from a t -dilate of ${\mathcal {P}}$ only by lattice points gained on the boundary.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Equivalently, ${\mathcal {P}}$ is reflexive if and only if its dual polytope ${\mathcal {P}}^{*}$ is an integral polytope.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Regular polytopes have the highest degree of symmetry of all polytopes.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] The symmetry group of a regular polytope acts transitively on its flags; hence, the dual polytope of a regular polytope is also regular.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Dimensions two, three and four include regular figures which have fivefold symmetries and some of which are non-convex stars, and in two dimensions there are infinitely many regular polygons of *n*-fold symmetry, both convex and (for *n* ≥ 5) star.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] But in higher dimensions there are no other regular polytopes.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In three dimensions the convex Platonic solids include the fivefold-symmetric dodecahedron and icosahedron, and there are also four star Kepler-Poinsot polyhedra with fivefold symmetry, bringing the total to nine regular polyhedra.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In four dimensions the regular 4-polytopes include one additional convex solid with fourfold symmetry and two with fivefold symmetry.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] There are ten star Schläfli-Hess 4-polytopes, all with fivefold symmetry, giving in all sixteen regular 4-polytopes.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] A non-convex polytope may be self-intersecting; this class of polytopes include the star polytopes.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] This generalizes Euler's formula for polyhedra.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Where a polytope is understood as a tiling or decomposition of a manifold, this idea may be extended to infinite manifolds.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Plane tilings, space-filling (honeycombs) and hyperbolic tilings are in this sense polytopes, and are sometimes called apeirotopes because they have infinitely many cells.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Among these, there are regular forms including the regular skew polyhedra and the infinite series of tilings represented by the regular apeirogon, square tiling, cubic honeycomb, and so on.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] The theory of abstract polytopes attempts to detach polytopes from the space containing them, considering their purely combinatorial properties.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] This allows the definition of the term to be extended to include objects for which it is difficult to define an intuitive underlying space, such as the 11-cell.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] An abstract polytope is a partially ordered set of elements or members, which obeys certain rules.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] It is a purely algebraic structure, and the theory was developed in order to avoid some of the issues which make it difficult to reconcile the various geometric classes within a consistent mathematical framework.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] A geometric polytope is said to be a realization in some real space of the associated abstract polytope.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Structures analogous to polytopes exist in complex Hilbert spaces $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ where *n* real dimensions are accompanied by *n* imaginary ones.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Regular complex polytopes are more appropriately treated as configurations.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] For an abstract polytope, this simply reverses the ordering of the set.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] This reversal is seen in the Schläfli symbols for regular polytopes, where the symbol for the dual polytope is simply the reverse of the original.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In the case of a geometric polytope, some geometric rule for dualising is necessary, see for example the rules described for dual polyhedra.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Depending on circumstance, the dual figure may or may not be another geometric polytope.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] If the dual is reversed, then the original polytope is recovered.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] If a polytope has the same number of vertices as facets, of edges as ridges, and so forth, and the same connectivities, then the dual figure will be similar to the original and the polytope is self-dual.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Polygons and polyhedra have been known since ancient times.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] An early hint of higher dimensions came in 1827 when August Ferdinand Möbius discovered that two mirror-image solids can be superimposed by rotating one of them through a fourth mathematical dimension.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] By the 1850s, a handful of other mathematicians such as Arthur Cayley and Hermann Grassmann had also considered higher dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Ludwig Schläfli was the first to consider analogues of polygons and polyhedra in these higher spaces.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] He described the six convex regular 4-polytopes in 1852 but his work was not published until 1901, six years after his death.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] By 1854, Bernhard Riemann's *Habilitationsschrift* had firmly established the geometry of higher dimensions, and thus the concept of *n*-dimensional polytopes was made acceptable.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Schläfli's polytopes were rediscovered many times in the following decades, even during his lifetime.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In 1882 Reinhold Hoppe, writing in German, coined the word *polytop* to refer to this more general concept of polygons and polyhedra.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In due course Alicia Boole Stott, daughter of logician George Boole, introduced the anglicised *polytope* into the English language.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In 1895, Thorold Gosset not only rediscovered Schläfli's regular polytopes but also investigated the ideas of semiregular polytopes and space-filling tessellations in higher dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Polytopes also began to be studied in non-Euclidean spaces such as hyperbolic space.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] An important milestone was reached in 1948 with H.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Coxeter's book *Regular Polytopes*, summarizing work to date and adding new findings of his own.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Meanwhile, the French mathematician Henri Poincaré had developed the topological idea of a polytope as the piecewise decomposition (e.g.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Branko Grünbaum published his influential work on *Convex Polytopes* in 1967.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In 1952 Geoffrey Colin Shephard generalised the idea as complex polytopes in complex space, where each real dimension has an imaginary one associated with it.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] The conceptual issues raised by complex polytopes, non-convexity, duality and other phenomena led Grünbaum and others to the more general study of abstract combinatorial properties relating vertices, edges, faces and so on.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] A related idea was that of incidence complexes, which studied the incidence or connection of the various elements with one another.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] These developments led eventually to the theory of abstract polytopes as partially ordered sets, or posets, of such elements.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Peter McMullen and Egon Schulte published their book *Abstract Regular Polytopes* in 2002.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] Enumerating the uniform polytopes, convex and nonconvex, in four or more dimensions remains an outstanding problem.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] The convex uniform 4-polytopes were fully enumerated by John Conway and Michael Guy using a computer in 1965; in higher dimensions this problem was still open as of 1997.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] The full enumeration for nonconvex uniform polytopes is not known in dimensions four and higher as of 2008.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In modern times, polytopes and related concepts have found many important applications in fields as diverse as computer graphics, optimization, search engines, cosmology, quantum mechanics and numerous other fields.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In 2013 the amplituhedron was discovered as a simplifying construct in certain calculations of theoretical physics.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In the field of optimization, linear programming studies the maxima and minima of linear functions; these maxima and minima occur on the boundary of an *n*-dimensional polytope.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In linear programming, polytopes occur in the use of generalized barycentric coordinates and slack variables.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] In twistor theory, a branch of theoretical physics, a polytope called the amplituhedron is used in to calculate the scattering amplitudes of subatomic particles when they collide.
[src:discrete-geometry/polytope] The construct is purely theoretical with no known physical manifestation, but is said to greatly simplify certain calculations.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] In geometry, a **sphere packing** is an arrangement of non-overlapping spheres within a containing space.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] However, sphere packing problems can be generalised to consider unequal spheres, spaces of other dimensions (where the problem becomes circle packing in two dimensions, or hypersphere packing in higher dimensions) or to non-Euclidean spaces such as hyperbolic space.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] A typical sphere packing problem is to find an arrangement in which the spheres fill as much of the space as possible.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] The proportion of space filled by the spheres is called the *packing density* of the arrangement.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] As the local density of a packing in an infinite space can vary depending on the volume over which it is measured, the problem is usually to maximise the average or asymptotic density, measured over a large enough volume.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] For equal spheres in three dimensions, the densest packing uses approximately 74% of the volume.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] A random packing of equal spheres generally has a density around 63.5%.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] A **lattice** arrangement (commonly called a **regular** arrangement) is one in which the points of the lattice form a very symmetric pattern that, in *n*-dimensional Euclidean space, needs only *n* vectors to be defined.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Lattice arrangements are periodic, and have the property that when the lattice is translated (moved) so that one point is placed where another was, the arrangement is the same as before.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Arrangements in which the points do not form a lattice can still be periodic, but also **aperiodic**, which includes **random** arrangements.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Lattice packings are easier to classify than those that are not lattices due to their high degree of symmetry.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Periodic lattices have well-defined densities.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] In three-dimensional Euclidean space, the densest packing of equal spheres is achieved by a family of structures called close-packed structures.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] One method for generating such a structure is as follows.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Consider a plane with a compact arrangement of spheres on it.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] For any three neighbouring spheres, a fourth sphere can be placed on top in the hollow between the three bottom spheres.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] If we do this for half of the holes in a second plane above the first, we create a new compact layer.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] There are two possible choices for doing this, call them B and C.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Then one half of the hollows of B lies above the centres of the balls in A and one half lies above the hollows of A that were not used for B.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Thus the balls of a third layer can be placed either directly above the balls of the first one, yielding a layer of type A, or above the holes of the first layer that were not occupied by the second layer, yielding a layer of type C.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Combining layers of types A, B, and C produces various close-packed structures.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Two simple arrangements within the close-packed family correspond to regular arrangements.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] One is called cubic close packing (or face-centred cubic, "FCC", which is a lattice)—where the layers are alternated in the ABCABC... sequence.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] The other is called hexagonal close packing ("HCP", which, although being a regular arrangement, is not a lattice), where the layers are alternated in the ABAB... sequence.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] But many layer stacking sequences are possible (ABAC, ABCBA, ABCBAC, etc.), and still generate a close-packed structure.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] In 1611, Johannes Kepler conjectured that this is the maximum possible density amongst both regular and irregular arrangements—this became known as the Kepler conjecture.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Carl Friedrich Gauss proved in 1831 that these packings have the highest density amongst all possible lattice packings.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] In 1998, Thomas Callister Hales, following the approach suggested by László Fejes Tóth in 1953, announced a proof of the Kepler conjecture.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Hales' proof is a proof by exhaustion involving checking of many individual cases using complex computer calculations.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Referees said that they were "99% certain" of the correctness of Hales' proof.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] On 10 August 2014, Hales announced the completion of a formal proof using automated proof checking, removing any doubt.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Some other lattice packings are often found in physical systems.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] These include the cubic lattice with a density of *π*/6 ≈ 0.5236, the hexagonal arrangement with a density of *π*/√27 ≈ 0.6046 and the tetrahedral arrangement with a density of *π*√3/16 ≈ 0.3401.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Packings where all spheres are constrained by their neighbours to stay in one location are called rigid or jammed.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] The strictly jammed (mechanically stable even as a finite system) regular sphere packing with the lowest known density is a diluted ("tunneled") fcc crystal with a density of only *π*√2/9 ≈ 0.49365.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] The loosest known regular jammed packing has a density of approximately 0.555.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] If we attempt to build a densely packed collection of spheres, we will be tempted to always place the next sphere in a hollow between three packed spheres.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] If five spheres are assembled in this way, they will be consistent with one of the regularly packed arrangements described above.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] However, the sixth sphere placed in this way will render the structure inconsistent with any regular arrangement.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] This results in the possibility of a *random close packing* of spheres that is stable against compression.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Vibration of a random loose packing can result in the arrangement of spherical particles into regular packings, a process known as granular crystallisation.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Such processes depend on the geometry of the container holding the spherical grains.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] When spheres are randomly added to a container and then compressed, they will generally form what is known as an "irregular" or "jammed" packing configuration when they can be compressed no more.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] This irregular packing will generally have a density of about 64%.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Recent research predicts analytically that it cannot exceed a density limit of 63.4% This situation is unlike the case of one or two dimensions, where compressing a collection of 1-dimensional or 2-dimensional spheres (that is, line segments or circles) will yield a regular packing.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] What is the densest sphere packing in dimensions other than 1, 2, 3, 8, and 24?
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] The sphere packing problem is the three-dimensional version of a class of ball-packing problems in arbitrary dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] In two dimensions, the equivalent problem is packing circles on a plane.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] In one dimension it is packing line segments into a linear universe.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] The densest lattice packings of hyperspheres are known for 1–8 and 24 dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Comparatively little is known about non-lattice hypersphere packings, the optimal result being known only in dimensions 1–3, 8, and 24; it is possible that in some dimensions the densest packing may be irregular.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Some support for this conjecture comes from the fact that in certain dimensions (e.g.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] 10) the densest known irregular packing is denser than the densest known regular packing.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] In 2016, Maryna Viazovska announced a proof that the E8 lattice, which has a packing density of ${\tfrac {\pi ^{4}}{2^{4}4!}}$ , provides the optimal packing (regardless of regularity) in eight-dimensional space.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Soon afterwards, she and a group of collaborators announced a similar proof that the Leech lattice, with a density of ${\tfrac {\pi ^{12}}{12!}}$ , is optimal in 24 dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] These results built on and improved previous methods that showed that these two lattices are very close to optimal.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Then, the Poisson summation formula for f is used to compare the density of the optimal lattice with that of any other packing.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Another line of research in high dimensions is trying to find asymptotic bounds for the density of the densest packings.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] It is known that for large n, the densest lattice in dimension n has density $\theta (n)$ between *cn* ⋅ 2−*n* (for some constant c) and 2−(0.599+o(1))*n*.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] In a 2023 preprint, Marcelo Campos, Matthew Jenssen, Marcus Michelen and Julian Sahasrabudhe announced an improvement to the lower bound of the maximal density to $\theta (n)\geq (1-o(1)){\frac {n\ln n}{2^{n+1}}}$ ; among their techniques they make use of the Rödl nibble.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] In an April 2025 preprint, Bo'az Klartag announced a significant further improvement: $\theta (n)\geq c{\frac {n^{2}}{2^{n}}}$ .
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Klartag sees his work as a stochastic evolution adaptation of the random lattice argument of C.A.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Many problems in the chemical and physical sciences can be related to packing problems where more than one size of sphere is available.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Here there is a choice between separating the spheres into regions of close-packed equal spheres, or combining the multiple sizes of spheres into a compound or interstitial packing.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] When many sizes of spheres (or a distribution) are available, the problem quickly becomes intractable, but some studies of binary hard spheres (two sizes) are available.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] When the second sphere is much smaller than the first, it is possible to arrange the large spheres in a close-packed arrangement, and then arrange the small spheres within the octahedral and tetrahedral gaps.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] The density of this interstitial packing depends sensitively on the radius ratio, but in the limit of extreme size ratios, the smaller spheres can fill the gaps with the same density as the larger spheres filled space.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Even if the large spheres are not in a close-packed arrangement, it is always possible to insert some smaller spheres of up to 0.29099 of the radius of the larger sphere.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] When the smaller sphere has a radius greater than 0.41421 of the radius of the larger sphere, it is no longer possible to fit into even the octahedral holes of the close-packed structure.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Thus, beyond this point, either the host structure must expand to accommodate the interstitials (which compromises the overall density), or rearrange into a more complex crystalline compound structure.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Structures are known that exceed the close packing density for radius ratios up to 0.659786.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Upper bounds for the density that can be obtained in such binary packings have also been obtained using a continuous analog of the sum of squares hierarchy of semidefinite programs.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] In many chemical situations such as ionic crystals, the stoichiometry is constrained by the charges of the constituent ions.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] This additional constraint on the packing, together with the need to minimize the Coulomb energy of interacting charges leads to a diversity of optimal packing arrangements.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] The upper bound for the density of a strictly jammed sphere packing with any set of radii is 1 – an example of such a packing of spheres is the Apollonian sphere packing.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] The lower bound for such a sphere packing is 0 – an example is the Dionysian sphere packing.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Although the concept of circles and spheres can be extended to hyperbolic space, finding the densest packing becomes much more difficult.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] In a hyperbolic space there is no limit to the number of spheres that can surround another sphere (for example, Ford circles can be thought of as an arrangement of identical hyperbolic circles in which each circle is surrounded by an infinite number of other circles).
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] The concept of average density also becomes much more difficult to define accurately.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] The densest packings in any hyperbolic space are almost always irregular.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Böröczky gives a universal upper bound for the density of sphere packings of hyperbolic *n*-space where *n* ≥ 2.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] In three dimensions the Böröczky bound is approximately 85.327613%, and is realized by the horosphere packing of the order-6 tetrahedral honeycomb with Schläfli symbol {3,3,6}.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] In addition to this configuration at least three other horosphere packings are known to exist in hyperbolic 3-space that realize the density upper bound.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] The contact graph of an arbitrary finite packing of unit balls is the graph whose vertices correspond to the packing elements and whose two vertices are connected by an edge if the corresponding two packing elements touch each other.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] In the case of 3-dimensional Euclidean space, non-trivial upper bounds on the number of touching pairs, triplets, and quadruples were proved by Karoly Bezdek and Samuel Reid at the University of Calgary.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] The problem of finding the arrangement of *n* identical spheres that maximizes the number of contact points between the spheres is known as the "sticky-sphere problem".
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] The maximum is known for *n* ≤ 11, and only conjectural values are known for larger *n*.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Sphere packing on the corners of a hypercube (with Hamming balls, spheres defined by Hamming distance) corresponds to designing error-correcting codes: if the spheres have radius *t*, then their centres are codewords of a (2*t* + 1)-error-correcting code.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] Lattice packings correspond to linear codes.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] There are other, subtler relationships between Euclidean sphere packing and error-correcting codes.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] For example, the binary Golay code is closely related to the 24-dimensional Leech lattice.
[src:discrete-geometry/sphere-packing] For further details on these connections, see the book *Sphere Packings, Lattices and Groups* by Conway and Sloane.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A **tessellation** or **tiling** is the covering of a surface, often a plane, using one or more geometric shapes, called *tiles*, with no overlaps and no gaps.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] In mathematics, tessellation can be generalized to higher dimensions and a variety of geometries.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A **periodic tiling** has a repeating pattern.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Some special kinds include *regular tilings* with regular polygonal tiles all of the same shape, and *semiregular tilings* with regular tiles of more than one shape and with every corner identically arranged.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The patterns formed by periodic tilings can be categorized into 17 wallpaper groups.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A tiling that lacks a repeating pattern is called "non-periodic".
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] An *aperiodic tiling* uses a small set of tile shapes that cannot form a repeating pattern (an aperiodic set of prototiles).
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A *tessellation of space*, also known as a space filling or honeycomb, can be defined in the geometry of higher dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A real physical tessellation is a tiling made of materials such as cemented ceramic squares or hexagons.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Such tilings may be decorative patterns, or may have functions such as providing durable and water-resistant pavement, floor, or wall coverings.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Historically, tessellations were used in Ancient Rome and in Islamic art such as in the Moroccan architecture and decorative geometric tiling of the Alhambra palace.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] In the twentieth century, the work of M.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Escher often made use of tessellations, both in ordinary Euclidean geometry and in hyperbolic geometry, for artistic effect.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tessellations are sometimes employed for decorative effect in quilting.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tessellations form a class of patterns in nature, for example in the arrays of hexagonal cells found in honeycombs.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tessellations were used by the Sumerians (about 4000 BC) in building wall decorations formed by patterns of clay tiles.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Decorative mosaic tilings made of small squared blocks called tesserae were widely employed in classical antiquity, sometimes displaying geometric patterns.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] In 1619, Johannes Kepler made an early documented study of tessellations.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] He wrote about regular and semiregular tessellations in his *Harmonices Mundi*; he was possibly the first to explore and to explain the hexagonal structures of honeycomb and snowflakes.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Some two hundred years later in 1891, the Russian crystallographer Yevgraf Fyodorov proved that every periodic tiling of the plane features one of seventeen different groups of isometries.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Fyodorov's work marked the unofficial beginning of the mathematical study of tessellations.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Other prominent contributors include Alexei Vasilievich Shubnikov and Nikolai Belov in their book *Colored Symmetry* (1964), and Heinrich Heesch and Otto Kienzle (1963).
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] In Latin, *tessella* is a small cubical piece of clay, stone, or glass used to make mosaics.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The word "tessella" means "small square" (from *tessera*, square, which in turn is from the Greek word τέσσερα for *four*).
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] It corresponds to the everyday term *tiling*, which refers to applications of tessellations, often made of glazed clay.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tessellation in two dimensions, also called planar tiling, is a topic in geometry that studies how shapes, known as *tiles*, can be arranged to fill a plane without any gaps, according to a given set of rules.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Common ones are that there must be no gaps between tiles, and that no corner of one tile can lie along the edge of another.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The tessellations created by bonded brickwork do not obey this rule.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Among those that do, a regular tessellation has both identical regular tiles and identical regular corners or vertices, having the same angle between adjacent edges for every tile.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] There are only three shapes that can form such regular tessellations: the equilateral triangle, square and the regular hexagon.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Any one of these three shapes can be duplicated infinitely to fill a plane with no gaps.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Many other types of tessellation are possible under different constraints.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] For example, there are eight types of semi-regular tessellation, made with more than one kind of regular polygon but still having the same arrangement of polygons at every corner.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Irregular tessellations can also be made from other shapes such as pentagons, polyominoes and in fact almost any kind of geometric shape.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Escher is famous for making tessellations with irregular interlocking tiles, shaped like animals and other natural objects.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] If suitable contrasting colours are chosen for the tiles of differing shape, striking patterns are formed, and these can be used to decorate physical surfaces such as church floors.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] More formally, a tessellation or tiling is a cover of the Euclidean plane by a countable number of closed sets, called *tiles*, such that the tiles intersect only on their boundaries.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] These tiles may be polygons or any other shapes.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Many tessellations are formed from a finite number of prototiles in which all tiles in the tessellation are congruent to the given prototiles.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] If a geometric shape can be used as a prototile to create a tessellation, the shape is said to *tessellate* or to *tile the plane*.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The Conway criterion is a sufficient, but not necessary, set of rules for deciding whether a given shape tiles the plane periodically without reflections: some tiles fail the criterion, but still tile the plane.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] No general rule has been found for determining whether a given shape can tile the plane or not, which means there are many unsolved problems concerning tessellations.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Mathematically, tessellations can be extended to spaces other than the Euclidean plane.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The Swiss geometer Ludwig Schläfli pioneered this by defining *polyschemes*, which mathematicians nowadays call polytopes.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] These are the analogues to polygons and polyhedra in spaces with more dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] He further defined the Schläfli symbol notation to make it easy to describe polytopes.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] For example, the Schläfli symbol for an equilateral triangle is {3}, while that for a square is {4}.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The Schläfli notation makes it possible to describe tilings compactly.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] For example, a tiling of regular hexagons has three six-sided polygons at each vertex, so its Schläfli symbol is {6,3}.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Other methods also exist for describing polygonal tilings.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] When the tessellation is made of regular polygons, the most common notation is the vertex configuration, which is simply a list of the number of sides of the polygons around a vertex.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The square tiling has a vertex configuration of 4.4.4.4, or 44.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The tiling of regular hexagons is noted 6.6.6, or 63.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Mathematicians use some technical terms when discussing tilings.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] An *edge* is the intersection between two bordering tiles; it is often a straight line.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A *vertex* is the point of intersection of three or more bordering tiles.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Using these terms, an *isogonal* or vertex-transitive tiling is a tiling where every vertex point is identical; that is, the arrangement of polygons about each vertex is the same.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The fundamental region is a shape such as a rectangle that is repeated to form the tessellation.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] For example, a regular tessellation of the plane with squares has a meeting of four squares at every vertex.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The sides of the polygons are not necessarily identical to the edges of the tiles.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] An **edge-to-edge tiling** is any polygonal tessellation where adjacent tiles only share one full side, i.e., no tile shares a partial side or more than one side with any other tile.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] In an edge-to-edge tiling, the sides of the polygons and the edges of the tiles are the same.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The familiar "brick wall" tiling is not edge-to-edge because the long side of each rectangular brick is shared with two bordering bricks.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A *normal tiling* is a tessellation for which every tile is topologically equivalent to a disk, the intersection of any two tiles is a connected set or the empty set, and all tiles are uniformly bounded.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] This means that a single circumscribing radius and a single inscribing radius can be used for all the tiles in the whole tiling; the condition disallows tiles that are pathologically long or thin.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A **monohedral tiling** is a tessellation in which all tiles are congruent; it has only one prototile.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A particularly interesting type of monohedral tessellation is the spiral monohedral tiling.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The first spiral monohedral tiling was discovered by Heinz Voderberg in 1936; the Voderberg tiling has a unit tile that is a nonconvex enneagon.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The **Hirschhorn tiling**, published by Michael D.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Hunt in 1985, is a pentagon tiling using irregular pentagons: regular pentagons cannot tile the Euclidean plane as the internal angle of a regular pentagon, ⁠3π/5⁠, is not a divisor of 2π.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] An isohedral tiling is a special variation of a monohedral tiling in which all tiles belong to the same transitivity class, that is, all tiles are transforms of the same prototile under the symmetry group of the tiling.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] If a prototile admits a tiling, but no such tiling is isohedral, then the prototile is called anisohedral and forms anisohedral tilings.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A regular tessellation is a highly symmetric, edge-to-edge tiling made up of regular polygons, all of the same shape.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] There are only three regular tessellations: those made up of equilateral triangles, squares, or regular hexagons.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] All three of these tilings are isogonal and monohedral.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A semi-regular (or Archimedean) tessellation uses more than one type of regular polygon in an isogonal arrangement.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] There are eight semi-regular tilings (or nine if the mirror-image pair of tilings counts as two).
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] These can be described by their vertex configuration; for example, a semi-regular tiling using squares and regular octagons has the vertex configuration 4.82 (each vertex has one square and two octagons).
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Many non-edge-to-edge tilings of the Euclidean plane are possible, including the family of Pythagorean tilings, tessellations that use two (parameterised) sizes of square, each square touching four squares of the other size.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] An edge tessellation is one in which each tile can be reflected over an edge to take up the position of a neighbouring tile, such as in an array of equilateral or isosceles triangles.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tilings with translational symmetry in two independent directions can be categorized by wallpaper groups, of which 17 exist.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] It has been claimed that all seventeen of these groups are represented in the Alhambra palace in Granada, Spain.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Although this is disputed, the variety and sophistication of the Alhambra tilings have interested modern researchers.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Of the three regular tilings two are in the *p6m* wallpaper group and one is in *p4m*.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tilings in 2-D with translational symmetry in just one direction may be categorized by the seven frieze groups describing the possible frieze patterns.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Orbifold notation can be used to describe wallpaper groups of the Euclidean plane.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Penrose tilings, which use two different quadrilateral prototiles, are the best known example of tiles that forcibly create non-periodic patterns.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] They belong to a general class of aperiodic tilings, which use tiles that cannot tessellate periodically.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The recursive process of substitution tiling is a method of generating aperiodic tilings.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] One class that can be generated in this way is the rep-tiles; these tilings have unexpected self-replicating properties.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Pinwheel tilings are non-periodic, using a rep-tile construction; the tiles appear in infinitely many orientations.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] It might be thought that a non-periodic pattern would be entirely without symmetry, but this is not so.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Aperiodic tilings, while lacking in translational symmetry, do have symmetries of other types, by infinite repetition of any bounded patch of the tiling and in certain finite groups of rotations or reflections of those patches.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A substitution rule, such as can be used to generate Penrose patterns using assemblies of tiles called rhombs, illustrates scaling symmetry.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A Fibonacci word can be used to build an aperiodic tiling, and to study quasicrystals, which are structures with aperiodic order.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Wang tiles are squares coloured on each edge, and placed so that abutting edges of adjacent tiles have the same colour; hence they are sometimes called Wang dominoes.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A suitable set of Wang dominoes can tile the plane, but only aperiodically.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] This is known because any Turing machine can be represented as a set of Wang dominoes that tile the plane if, and only if, the Turing machine does not halt.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Since the halting problem is undecidable, the problem of deciding whether a Wang domino set can tile the plane is also undecidable.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Truchet tiles are square tiles decorated with patterns so they do not have rotational symmetry; in 1704, Sébastien Truchet used a square tile split into two triangles of contrasting colours.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] These can tile the plane either periodically or randomly.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] An *einstein tile* is a single shape that forces aperiodic tiling.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The first such tile, dubbed a "hat", was discovered in 2023 by David Smith, a hobbyist mathematician.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The discovery is under professional review and, upon confirmation, will be credited as solving a longstanding mathematical problem.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Sometimes the colour of a tile is understood as part of the tiling; at other times arbitrary colours may be applied later.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] When discussing a tiling that is displayed in colours, to avoid ambiguity, one needs to specify whether the colours are part of the tiling or just part of its illustration.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] This affects whether tiles with the same shape, but different colours, are considered identical, which in turn affects questions of symmetry.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The four colour theorem states that for every tessellation of a normal Euclidean plane, with a set of four available colours, each tile can be coloured in one colour such that no tiles of equal colour meet at a curve of positive length.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The colouring guaranteed by the four colour theorem does not generally respect the symmetries of the tessellation.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] To produce a colouring that does, it is necessary to treat the colours as part of the tessellation.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Here, as many as seven colours may be needed, as demonstrated in the image at left.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Next to the various tilings by regular polygons, tilings by other polygons have also been studied.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Any triangle or quadrilateral (even non-convex) can be used as a prototile to form a monohedral tessellation, often in more than one way.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Copies of an arbitrary quadrilateral can form a tessellation with translational symmetry and 2-fold rotational symmetry with centres at the midpoints of all sides.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] For an asymmetric quadrilateral this tiling belongs to wallpaper group p2.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] As fundamental domain we have the quadrilateral.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Equivalently, we can construct a parallelogram subtended by a minimal set of translation vectors, starting from a rotational centre.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] We can divide this by one diagonal, and take one half (a triangle) as fundamental domain.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Such a triangle has the same area as the quadrilateral and can be constructed from it by cutting and pasting.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] If only one shape of tile is allowed, tilings exist with convex *N*-gons for *N* equal to 3, 4, 5, and 6.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] For *N* = 5, see Pentagonal tiling, for *N* = 6, see Hexagonal tiling, for *N* = 7, see Heptagonal tiling and for *N* = 8, see octagonal tiling.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] With non-convex polygons, there are far fewer limitations in the number of sides, even if only one shape is allowed.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Polyominoes are examples of tiles that are either convex of non-convex, for which various combinations, rotations, and reflections can be used to tile a plane.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] For results on tiling the plane with polyominoes, see Polyomino § Uses of polyominoes.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Voronoi or Dirichlet tilings are tessellations where each tile is defined as the set of points closest to one of the points in a discrete set of defining points.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] (Think of geographical regions where each region is defined as all the points closest to a given city or post office.) The *Voronoi cell* for each defining point is a convex polygon.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The Delaunay triangulation is a tessellation that is the dual graph of a Voronoi tessellation.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Delaunay triangulations are useful in numerical simulation, in part because among all possible triangulations of the defining points, Delaunay triangulations maximize the minimum of the angles formed by the edges.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Voronoi tilings with randomly placed points can be used to construct random tilings of the plane.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tessellation can be extended to three dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Certain polyhedra can be stacked in a regular crystal pattern to fill (or tile) three-dimensional space, including the cube (the only Platonic polyhedron to do so), the rhombic dodecahedron, the truncated octahedron, and triangular, quadrilateral, and hexagonal prisms, among others.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Any polyhedron that fits this criterion is known as a plesiohedron, and may possess between 4 and 38 faces.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Naturally occurring rhombic dodecahedra are found as crystals of andradite (a kind of garnet) and fluorite.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tessellations in three or more dimensions are called honeycombs.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] In three dimensions there is just one regular honeycomb, which has eight cubes at each polyhedron vertex.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Similarly, in three dimensions there is just one quasiregular honeycomb, which has eight tetrahedra and six octahedra at each polyhedron vertex.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] However, there are many possible semiregular honeycombs in three dimensions.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Uniform honeycombs can be constructed using the Wythoff construction.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The Schmitt-Conway biprism is a convex polyhedron with the property of tiling space only aperiodically.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A Schwarz triangle is a spherical triangle that can be used to tile a sphere.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] It is possible to tessellate in non-Euclidean geometries such as hyperbolic geometry.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] A uniform honeycomb in hyperbolic space is a uniform tessellation of uniform polyhedral cells.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] In three-dimensional (3-D) hyperbolic space there are nine Coxeter group families of compact convex uniform honeycombs, generated as Wythoff constructions, and represented by permutations of rings of the Coxeter diagrams for each family.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] In architecture, tessellations have been used to create decorative motifs since ancient times.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Mosaic tilings often had geometric patterns.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Later civilisations also used larger tiles, either plain or individually decorated.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Some of the most decorative were the Moorish wall tilings of Islamic architecture, using Girih and Zellige tiles in buildings such as the Alhambra and La Mezquita.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tessellations frequently appeared in the graphic art of M.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Escher; he was inspired by the Moorish use of symmetry in places such as the Alhambra when he visited Spain in 1936.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Escher made four "Circle Limit" drawings of tilings that use hyperbolic geometry.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] For his woodcut "Circle Limit IV" (1960), Escher prepared a pencil and ink study showing the required geometry.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tessellated designs often appear on textiles, whether woven, stitched in, or printed.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tessellation patterns have been used to design interlocking motifs of patch shapes in quilts.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tessellations are also a main genre in origami, where pleats are used to connect molecules, such as twist folds, together in a repeating fashion.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tessellation is used in manufacturing industry to reduce the wastage of material (yield losses) such as sheet metal when cutting out shapes for objects such as car doors or drink cans.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tessellation is apparent in the mudcrack-like cracking of thin films – with a degree of self-organisation being observed using micro and nanotechnologies.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The honeycomb is a well-known example of tessellation in nature with its hexagonal cells.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] In botany, the term "tessellate" describes a checkered pattern, for example on a flower petal, tree bark, or fruit.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Flowers including the fritillary, and some species of *Colchicum*, are characteristically tessellate.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Many patterns in nature are formed by cracks in sheets of materials.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] These patterns can be described by Gilbert tessellations, also known as random crack networks.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The Gilbert tessellation is a mathematical model for the formation of mudcracks, needle-like crystals, and similar structures.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The model, named after Edgar Gilbert, allows cracks to form starting from being randomly scattered over the plane; each crack propagates in two opposite directions along a line through the initiation point, its slope chosen at random, creating a tessellation of irregular convex polygons.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Basaltic lava flows often display columnar jointing as a result of contraction forces causing cracks as the lava cools.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] The extensive crack networks that develop often produce hexagonal columns of lava.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] One example of such an array of columns is the Giant's Causeway in Northern Ireland.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tessellated pavement, a characteristic example of which is found at Eaglehawk Neck on the Tasman Peninsula of Tasmania, is a rare sedimentary rock formation where the rock has fractured into rectangular blocks.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Other natural patterns occur in foams; these are packed according to Plateau's laws, which require minimal surfaces.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Such foams present a problem in how to pack cells as tightly as possible: in 1887, Lord Kelvin proposed a packing using only one solid, the bitruncated cubic honeycomb with very slightly curved faces.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] In 1993, Denis Weaire and Robert Phelan proposed the Weaire–Phelan structure, which uses less surface area to separate cells of equal volume than Kelvin's foam.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Tessellations have given rise to many types of tiling puzzle, from traditional jigsaw puzzles (with irregular pieces of wood or cardboard) and the tangram, to more modern puzzles that often have a mathematical basis.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] For example, polyiamonds and polyominoes are figures of regular triangles and squares, often used in tiling puzzles.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Authors such as Henry Dudeney and Martin Gardner have made many uses of tessellation in recreational mathematics.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] For example, Dudeney invented the hinged dissection, while Gardner wrote about the "rep-tile", a shape that can be dissected into smaller copies of the same shape.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Inspired by Gardner's articles in Scientific American, the amateur mathematician Marjorie Rice found four new tessellations with pentagons.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] Squaring the square is the problem of tiling an integral square (one whose sides have integer length) using only other integral squares.
[src:discrete-geometry/tessellation] An extension is squaring the plane, tiling it by squares whose sizes are all natural numbers without repetitions; James and Frederick Henle proved that this was possible.
